Uncinate process lies superior to superior mesenteric vessels"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pancreas has several key anatomical relationships with surrounding structures. The pancreatic \u003Cstrong\u003Eneck\u003C/strong\u003E lies posterior to the formation of the portal vein where the superior mesenteric and splenic veins join, making this the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pancreatic \u003Cstrong\u003Ebody\u003C/strong\u003E lies posterior to the splenic artery, not anterior to it. The pancreatic \u003Cstrong\u003Ehead\u003C/strong\u003E lies posterior to the superior mesenteric vessels and anterior to the aorta, rather than anterior to the inferior vena cava. The pancreatic \u003Cstrong\u003Etail\u003C/strong\u003E extends into the splenorenal ligament in the peritoneal cavity near the splenic hilum, not in the retroperitoneal space. The \u003Cstrong\u003Euncinate process\u003C/strong\u003E hooks beneath (inferior to) the superior mesenteric artery and vein, not superior to these vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The pancreatic neck lies posterior to the formation of the portal vein","The uncinate process hooks beneath (inferior to) the superior mesenteric vessels","The pancreatic tail is located in the peritoneal cavity near the splenic hilum"],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95955"}},"question":{"data"